ven greater importance is that society at large now realizes that mountains and the people who reside in them are not isolated from the mainstream of world affairs, but are vital if we are to achieve an environmentally sustainable future. Mountain Geography is a comprehensive resource that gives readers an in-depth understanding of the geographical processes occurring in the world’s mountains and the overall impact of these regions on culture and society as a whole. The volume begins with an introduction to how mountains are defined, followed by a comprehensive treatment of their physical geography: origins, climatology, snow and ice, landforms and geomorphic processes, soils, vegetation, and wildlife. The concluding chapters provide an introduction to the human geography of mountains: attitudes toward mountains, people living in mountain regions and their livelihoods and interactions within dynamic environments, the diverse types of mountain agriculture, and the challenges of sustainable mountain development.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGeomorphology. 0aHuman geography. 0aMountain people. 0aMountains. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Geography.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  acomprehensive resource.  aconservation.  acritical resources.  adynamic environments.  aearth science.  aearth sciences.  aecology.  aenvironmental.  ageographical processes.  ageography.  ageology.  ageomorphic processes.  agives readers.  aglobal importance.  aglobal population.  ahuman geography.  alandforms.  amountain agriculture.  amountain ranges.  amountains.  anature.  aphysical geography.  ascience.  asustainale mountain development.  awater resources.  awilderness.1 aBach, Andrew J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernbaum, Edwin, econtrib